revision.text:
'''Epameinondas Kavvadias''' ({{lang-el|Επαμεινώνδας Καββαδίας}}, 1886–1965) was a [[Greece|Greek]] admiral who served thrice as Chief of the [[Hellenic Navy General Staff|Navy General Staff]] and led the Greek fleet in the first years of [[World War II]].

== Life ==
Born in [[Athens]] in 1886 to a family hailing from [[Cephalonia]], Kavvadias entered the [[Hellenic Naval Academy]] in 1902 and graduated in 1906, and served in the [[Royal Hellenic Navy]] in the [[Balkan Wars]] as a [[Sub-lieutenant]] in the destroyer ''[[Greek destroyer Nafkratousa|Nafkratousa]]''. During the [[Asia Minor Campaign]], he commanded the destroyers ''[[Greek destroyer Thyella|Thyella]]'' and ''[[Greek destroyer Niki|Niki]]''. He was dismissed from the Navy in 1922, dollowing the [[September 1922 Revolution]], due to his royalist convictions, but reinstated by the [[Theodoros Pangalos (general)|Theodoros Pangalos]] dictatorship in 1925.

As [[Captain (naval)|Captain]], he served his first tenure as Chief of the [[Hellenic Navy General Staff|Navy General Staff]] in 1933–1934. In 1935 he was appointed to the post of Commander of the submarine fleet, and served again for a short period at the head of the Navy General Staff in December 1936 – January 1937. He subsequently served as Chief of the Royal Naval Base at [[Salamis Island|Salamis]] until 1939, including another short term at the head of the General Staff in August–September 1938. Promoted to [[Rear Admiral]] in the meantime, in September 1939 he was appointed Chief of the Fleet Command. He led the operations of the Greek fleet during the [[Greco-Italian War]] of 1940–1941, and following the [[German invasion of Greece]] in April 1941, led the fleet to its exile in the British-held [[Middle East]]. He remained Chief of the Fleet until 2 May 1942, when he was appointed Vice Minister of Naval Affairs in the [[Greek government in exile]], a post he held until 25 March 1943. In 1946, he was sent to [[London]] as [[naval attaché]]. In 1950, he published his war memoirs under the title ''The naval war of 1940 as I experienced it'' ("Ο ναυτικός πόλεμος του 1940 όπως τον έζησα"). 

He died in Athens on 10 April 1965.<ref name="PN">{{cite web | url = http://www.hellenicnavy.gr/el/organwsi/geniko-epiteleio-naftikou/diatelesantes-arxigoi-gen/206-gr/viografika/2015-03-23-19-16-51/1042-2015-03-23-19-38-35 | title = Διατελέσαντες Αρχηγοί ΓΕΝ: Καββαδίας, Επαμεινώνδας  | publisher = [[Hellenic Navy]] | language = Greek | accessdate = 10 May 2015}}</ref>

== Honours ==
Among other Greek and foreign medals, Kavvadias received:
* [[Cross of Valour (Greece)|Commander's Cross of the Cross of Valour]] (1 July 1947), Greece's highest military award, for his overall leadership of the fleet in World War II<ref name="PN"/>
* [[Medal for Outstanding Acts]] (31 August 1946), for his role in the reorganization of the fleet in exile<ref name="PN"/>
* [[War Cross (Greece)#1940 version|War Cross 1st Class]] (31 August 1946), for the Greco-Italian War<ref name="PN"/>
* [[War Cross (Greece)#1940 version|War Cross 2nd Class]] (14 September 1944), for the Navy's evacuation in April 1941<ref name="PN"/>
* [[War Cross (Greece)#1940 version|War Cross 2nd Class]] (27 October 1941), for the Greco-Italian War<ref name="PN"/>
* [[Cross of Valour (Greece)|Cross of Valour in Gold]] (25 February 1922), for the [[Asia Minor Campaign]]<ref name="PN"/>

He was also named honorary [[aide de camp]] to King [[Paul of Greece|Paul]] in 1947, and Honorary Chief of the Fleet in 1963.<ref name="PN"/>

